{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639836"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:10:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:10:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17792"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17792"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.79,0.03,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78463"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10506"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63825"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9934"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25009"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78463"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETissue metabolism affects local oxygen delivery through changes in the chemical environment around haemoglobin molecules.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the Bohr effect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Heat production alters haemoglobin binding","Rising carbon dioxide reduces oxygen affinity","Falling carbon dioxide increases oxygen release","Rising carbon dioxide enhances oxygen binding","Oxygen saturation controls carbon dioxide transport"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erising carbon dioxide reduces oxygen affinity\u003C/strong\u003E, known as the Bohr effect. As tissues metabolise nutrients, they produce carbon dioxide which forms carbonic acid and hydrogen ions. This acidic environment decreases haemoglobin\u0027s ability to bind oxygen, facilitating oxygen release in metabolically active regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERising carbon dioxide enhances oxygen binding\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the opposite of what actually occurs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFalling carbon dioxide increases oxygen release\u003C/strong\u003E - This is physiologically incorrect as less CO2 actually increases O2 binding\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen saturation controls carbon dioxide transport\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the Haldane effect, a separate phenomenon\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeat production alters haemoglobin binding\u003C/strong\u003E - While temperature affects binding, this is not the Bohr effect\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis mechanism ensures tissues receiving more oxygen when their metabolic activity and thus carbon dioxide production increases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Carbon dioxide production causes decreased haemoglobin affinity for oxygen via pH changes, shifting the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve rightward.","Local acidosis from tissue metabolism promotes oxygen unloading from haemoglobin where needed.","This physiological mechanism helps match oxygen delivery to metabolic demand in tissues."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63825"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17792"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63825"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T20:59:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T20:59:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10506"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78463"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"